<subsection xml:id="subsec-expressing-probability-outcomes-in-decimals-in-different-situations">
    <title>Expressing probability outcomes in decimals  in different situations</title>
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Materials Needed:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Small colored objects (like beads or buttons) in 3 colors to represent watermelons, bananas, and mangoes.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    E.g., green = watermelon, yellow = banana, orange = mango.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Small paper bags or containers
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Worksheets or notebooks for recording answers
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Calculators (optional)
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Place 7 green, 5 yellow, and 3 orange items into a bag to represent watermelons, bananas, and mangoes respectively, for a total of 15 fruits.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Each student draws one item from the bag without looking, records the color (fruit), then returns it to the bag, repeating this process 10 times.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Calculate:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Count how many times they picked each color (fruit).
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Then calculate the experimental probability for each fruit:
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Write your answer in decimal form.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Discuss and share your answer with other groups.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Expressing probability outcomes in decimals}</m> means representing the likelihood of events using numbers between 0 and 1 (eg 0.25), where:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                0 represents an impossible event (0% chance).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                1 represents a certain event (100% chance).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Any number between 0 and 1 (like 0.25, 0.5, 0.75) shows how likely the event is:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            0.5 = 50% chance (like flipping a fair coin and getting heads).
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            0.25 = 25% chance.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            0.75 = 75% chance.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Probabilities always add up to 1.0.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A bag contains seven watermelons, five bananas and three mangoes. What is the probability that a fruit selected at random is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A watermelon? 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A banana?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A mango?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                Express the answer as a decimal.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Watermelons = <m>7</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Bananas = <m>5</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Mangoes = <m>3</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Total number of fruits  <m>7+5+3 = 15</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculating the probability of selecting a watermelon, we use formula:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\textbf{P(Watermelon)} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Number of possible outcomes of a watermelon}}{\textbf{Total number of fruits}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{7}{15}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 0.4667</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, the probability of selcting a watermelon is <m>0.4667</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculating the probability of selecting a banana, we use formula:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\textbf{P(Banana)} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Number of possible outcomes of a banana}}{\textbf{Total number of fruits}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{5}{15}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{3}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 0.3333</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, the probability of selcting a banana is <m>0.3333</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculating the probability of selecting a mango, we use formula:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\textbf{P(Mango)} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Number of possible outcomes of a mango}}{\textbf{Total number of fruits}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{3}{15}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{5}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 0.2</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, the probability of selcting a mango is <m>0.2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In a school with <m>50</m> students, <m>12</m> students have a bicycle. What is the probability that a student picked at random owns a bicycle? Write the answer in decimal form.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The total number of students is: <m>50</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                The number of students who own a bicycle is: <m>12</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Using the probability formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{Probability} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Number of favorable outcomes}}{\textbf{Total number of outcomes}}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =  \amp \frac{12}{50}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =  \amp 0.24</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                So, the probability that a randomly selected student owns a bicycle is <m>0.24</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    
</subsection>